- arr[i] are all equal for every 0 <= i < arr.length - 1.\nA value from arr was removed that was not the first or last value in the array.\nGiven arr, return the removed value.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: arr = [5,7,11,13]\nOutput: 9\nExplanation: The previous array was [5,7,9,11,13].\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: arr = [15,13,12]\nOutput: 14\nExplanation: The previous array was [15,14,13,12].\n \nConstraints:\n\n3 <= arr.length <= 1000\n0 <= arr[i] <= 105\nThe given array is guaranteed to be a valid array.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def missingNumber(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def missingNumber(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Calculate the length of the original array\n        n = len(arr) + 1\n        \n        # Calculate the expected sum of the arithmetic progression\n        expected_sum = (n * (arr[0] + arr[-1])) // 2\n        \n        # Calculate the actual sum of the given array\n        actual_sum = sum(arr)\n        \n        # The missing number is the difference between the expected sum and the actual sum\n        return expected_sum - actual_sum\n```\n\nThis solution works by leveraging the properties of arithmetic progressions. The sum of an arithmetic progression can be calculated using the formula: \n\n\\[ \\text{Sum} = \\frac{n}{2} \\times (\\text{first\\_term} + \\text{last\\_term}) \\]\n\nWhere \\( n \\) is the number of terms in the progression. By calculating the expected sum of the original array (which includes the missing number) and subtracting the actual sum of the given array, we can find the missing number.", "estimated_date": 1570924800000}